The size of the growth prohibition area on the provided bacterium are measured for disk diffusion, and the findings are presented in Table 3
                        . As well as shown in Table 2, no zone of inhibition was observed for Cu3Mo2O9 and Cu3Mo2O9/GQDs nanostructures against E. faecalis and P. aeruginosa. In treatment with Cu3Mo2O9 NPs, the size of growth prohibition area against S. aureus, MRSA, S. epidermidis, S. saprophyticus, E. coli, S. flexneri, Salmonella, and K. pneumonia were measured 18, 12, 20, 27, 10, 16, 17, and 5 mm, respectively (Fig. 10
                        ). Overall, by comparing the obtained results from Cu3Mo2O9 NPs and Cu3Mo2O9/GQDs NCs, it is found that the antibacterial activity of Cu3Mo2O9/GQDs NCs is slightly better than Cu3Mo2O9 NPs. Against S. aureus, there is a significant difference between Cu3Mo2O9 NPs and Cu3Mo2O9/GQDs NCs. For the Cu3Mo2O9/GQDs NCs, the size of growth prohibition area against S. aureus, MRSA, S. epidermidis, S. saprophyticus, E. coli, S. flexneri, and Salmonella were measured 23, 15, 20, 27, 10, 17, and 15 respectively (Fig. 11
                        ). Surprisingly, Cu3Mo2O9/GQDs NCs have no significant effect on K. pneumonia, unlike Cu3Mo2O9 NPs. Improvement of antibacterial activity in Cu3Mo2O9/GQDs NCs case can be explained as the following mechanism: the presence of GQDs in Cu3Mo2O9/GQDs NCs can improve photocatalytic performance and subsequently produce more reactive oxygen species (ROS) which are responsible for stopping the growth of microorganisms because of copper molybdates are visible-active semiconductor that produce electron–hole pairs under visible irradiation [28]. On the other words, it is well known that molybdenum-containing nanomaterials show excellent photo-response characteristics which leads the transition of an electron from the valence band to the conduction band, creating free electron and holes pair. GQDs facilitate electron–hole formation in Cu3Mo2O9/GQDs NCs. These carriers come into the surface of Cu3Mo2O9/GQDs NCs and react with an oxygen-containing compound of medium and produce reactive oxygen species. As a result, oxygen and hydroxyl radicals are formed. These reactive oxygen species penetrate to the cell wall and elevate the oxidative stress response of the bacteria, leading to metabolic dysfunction of cells and bacterial destruction [29–34]. One of the reasons for this phenomenon is the surface increased by preparation of nanocomposite base on graphene quantum dots, as mentioned.
